{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_melville_ver02/data/sn84026749/0022225405A/1923122101/0796.xml":{"full_text":"18\nCAPPER VISIONS\nBETTER DAYS\nONFARMS\nAgriculture Slowly Recovering\nProsperity\u2014Legislative\nI. Aid Needed.\nBy KENNETH CLARK\nInternational News Sen-ice.\n(Copyright, 1923, by International\nNews Service.)\nAmerican agriculture is slowly\nclimbing out of the slump and all\nIndications point to a substantial\nimprovement in the industry dur\ning the new year, Senator Arthur\nCapper (Rep.), of Kansas, declared\ntoday in an interview with Inter\nnational News Service.\nCapper, leader of the farm bloc\nin Congress, is recognized as one\nof America\u2019s foremost authorities\non agriculture.\n\u201cAll indications point to a- grad\nual improvement in the farmers\u2019\neconomic position during the new\nyear,\u201d Capper said.\n\"The wheat farmer, of course, is\nnot yet out of the ditch. For three\nyears he has produced wheat at a\nloss. But another year should\nshow an improvement. The wheat\nfarmer is curtailing his acreage,\ncutting his production to meet\nmore nearly the requirements of\nthe home market and avoiding sur\nplus production which is always\ndisastrous to him. Figures and\nestimates now available indicate a\nreduction of wheat acreage of about\nIS per cent.\nHas Long Wa) to Go.\n\u201cBetter business methods, co-op\neration in the marketing of prod\nucts, and some decrease in the\nspread between the cost of things\nbe sells will contribute to the im\nprovement in the farmers\u2019 economic\nposition. He still has a long way\nto go before his prosperity is com\npletely restored. He still is at the\nbottom of the ladder in comparison\nwith other industries! He must\nhave sympathetic consideration in\nany scheme looking toward the as\nsurance of national prosperity dur\ning the new year.\n\u201cHis most pressing need is relief\nfrom excessive transportation costs.\nI hope to see substantial reduction\nin freight rates at an early date.\n\"With ampler credit facilities,\nbetter marketing methods and re\nduction of acreage more nearly to\nbring crop yields within the require\nments of the home market demand,\nthe new year should see a market\nimprovement\u2014particularly in re\ngard to the wheat grower who last\nyear did not share in the upturn\nin favor of agriculture as a whole.\nTax Adjustment Needed.\n\u201cAmong legislative influences that\nshould have a favorable effect on\nthe agricultural industry during the\nyear, reduction of war taxes is out\nStanding. This should ease the\nburden that productive enterprise\nand business is now forced to carry.\n\"It is absurdly unfair that earned\nincome should be penalized and\nunearned income eased of its share\nof the costs of government and the\nliquidation of war obligations. Abo\nlition of the tax exempt privilege\nwould go far toward a more equita\nble distribution of the tax load.\n\"Whatever tax legislation is writ\nten should be written on the basis\nof such distribution, share and\nshare alike according to ability to\npay.\nFinds Freights Too High.\n\"Next in importance, perhaps, to\nthe welfare of business is the read\njustment of freight rates. Discrim\ninatory and confiscatory freights\nare a major factor in the delay of\nthe farmers\u2019 economic recovery.\n\"In the solution of this problem\nthe farmer is entitled to the sym-i\npathetic attention and co-operation\nof all business men, for the farmer\nis not only a producer; he is nor\nmally a consumer.\n\"As his re.turn to prosperity is\npostponed, his disadvantage affects\nthe entire business community,\"\nCapper concluded.\nUNDERWDODHAS\nBATTLE ON IN\nALABAMA\nPlan Is Formed Here to Beat\nHim in PrimaTy Contest\nfor Delegates.\nBy JOHN T. LAMBERT,\nCosmopolitan News Service.\nAn aggressive campaign to de\nfeat United States Senator Oscar\nW. Underwood in his home state of\nAlabama and thereby drive him\nout of the race for President is be\ning framed here in Washington to\nday.\nL. B. Musgrove will probably be\nhit upon by all the anti-Under\nwood forces as the man most tal\nented to make the campaign against\nUnderwood. Musgrove is believed\nto be William J. Bryan\u2019s \u201cda.rk\nhorse\u201d candidate for President.\nMay Unite Foes.\nUnderwood has staunch friends\nand equally bitter enemies in his i\nhome state. Organized labor, the!\ndrys and the progressives there are\nespecially bitter. Underwood\u2019s\nforces recently stirred up a new\nopposition by forcing through the\nlocal legislature a law which pro\nvides that the citizens of Alabama\nwho polls the most votes for Presi\ndent in the coming Presidential pri\nmaries shall be allowed to pieg the\ndelegates to the national Democratic\nconvention. The new law was in\nterpreted as a scheme of the Under\nwood forces to deprive any other\ncandidate, notably McAdoo of a fair\nchance to beat Underwood.\nMusgrove has leen sitting fr. nt\nconferences in Washington with\nnumerous friends who are prevail\ning upon him to become the can\ndidate against Underwood. For\nWITH THE\nALIBI\nARTISTS\nTHE TRAFFIC COURT\nIN CROSS SECTION\nBeing a Skeleton Record\nOs Cases Tried in Judge\nSchuldt\u2019s Tribunal.\nRead \u2019Em And Worry\nBy DONALD McDOUGAL.\nImmature Truck Drivers.\n\"My two sisters were in the\ncoupe with me, your honor, about\n5 o\u2019clock in the evening, Decem\nber 5. We were running east on\nC street northeast and had passed\na little more than half way over\nSeventh street when I saw the\nheadlights of a machine on my\nleft coming toward me at a high\nrate of speed.\nAnd Work for Suffrage, Too.\n\"My husband told me that in\na case of that sort I should turn\nin the direction the other ma\nchine was going. I did that and\nsaw a lot of stars, and my head\nwas aching dreadfully, but the\ninterne told the nurse to put an\nice-bag on and I felt better.\nThat\u2019s all I know about it.\u201d\nGoes to Right Shop.\nLittle sister: I\u2014was sitting on\nthe right side of the coupe, and\nwhen we were about half way\nacross Seventh street on C street,\nI saw the Reflection of a bright\nlight on the side of our car, and\nI knew we were going to be run\ndbwn. The seat seemed to slide\nout from under me and when my\neyes opened I saw a big sign that\nread, \u2019Drink Swamp Root for\nthat Run-Down Feeling.\u2019 The\ndruggist poured something out of\na bottle and gave it to me. Then\nthey put me in the ambulance.\u201d\nWho\u2019s Next?\nBig sister: \u201cI was seated be\ntween my two sisters and could\nnot see what was goinfr on very\nwell. I heard a crash and a\ncrunch and knew we- had been\nhit.\u201d\n'\"What was the position of the\ncar after the collision?\u201d\n\"Upside down.\u201d\n\"I mean, what part of the street\nwas it in?\u201d\nT don\u2019t know. I never opened\nmy eyes until I got to the hos\npital.\u201d\nWitness: \"I was walking on\nthe east side of Seventh street,\njust getting ready to cross C,\nwhen I saw the lights of the\ncoupe approaching on my left.\nThe weather was drizzly, and the\nstreets were pretty wet, so I con\ncluded to wait until the coupe had\npassed.\nA Jump In Time.\n\"Then I saw the lights of the\ntruck about half way up the\nblack pretty well over on the\nwrong side and coming like a\nstreak. It reached the north build\ning line of C street when the\ncoupe was about half way across\nSeventh, and it looked to me like\na sure thing collision. I figured\nthat the cars would land jugt\nabout where I was standing, and\nit seemed as though there\u2019d be\nenough corpses without mine, and\nI got away from there just as the\ncars crashed.\nOn the Sidewalks of Washington.\n\"Then I ran back the 200 feet\nto the corner and helped the ladies\nout of the coupe. The truck had\nrun up onto the sidewalk with\nthe rear wheel where I\u2019d been\nstanding, knocked down police\npatrol box No. 12, poked Jts bump\ner through the fence, and- was\nlying upside down when we be\ngan searching the ruins for the\ndriver. He wasn\u2019t there.\nNext Witness: \"I had turned\ninto C street from Eighth, your\nhonor, when the truck ran across\nC street and hit the coupe. I\nspeeded up to give any help that\nmight be necessary, and was step\nping out .of my machine when I\nsaw a mdn crawl from under the\ntruck and- run down Seventh\nstreet.\nThey Always Get \u2019Em.\n\"Someone was yelling, \u2018There\u2019s\nthree women pinned under the\ncoupe. For God\u2019s sake get \u2019em\nout.\u2019 So I went over to the coupe\nInstead of chasing the runaway.\nBut I recognized the truck, and\nhad a pretty fair idea of who\nwas driving it, and gave his name\nto the police.\u2019\nBut the Truck Was Full Grown.\nCounsel: \"We contend that there\nwas no collision, your honor.\nEach car made a sudden turn to\navoid the other, and was upset\nthereby. We admit that the de\nfendant ran away, but that was\nbecause he was scared half to\ndeath. He\u2019s only a kid\u2014\u201d\n\"How old is he?\u2019\u2019\n\u201cBoob: \"Eighteen, your hohor.\u201d\nIt\u2019s Still up to Congress.\nThe court: \u2019This is another case\nof immature driver. The court\nagrees with counsel that the em\nployer is culpable for sending out\nan Irresponsible youth with such\na deadly instrument. That the\ndefendant had no permit was\nknown to the employer, too, the\nevidence shows. But if he were\nbrought into court he would prob\nably deny it. The burden should\nbe put on employers to find out\nwhether their drivers have per\nmits or not. This is-not an un\nreasonable demand, because all\nthey need to do is call for the\npermits. It is the merest good\nfortune that five people were not\nkilled in this case.\"\nReckless driving, $100; leaving\nafter colliding, S3O; no permit, S2O.\nmany years he has been a con\nspicuous figure although not an of\nfice seeker, in Alabama politics. He\nis a bachelor, well over fifty, com\nfortably fixed in worldly goods,\nenjoys politics and has been one\nof the most generous contributors\nto the prohibition forces in the\nSouth. He organized the last\nsenatorial campaign against Under\nwood and all but defeated him.\nPrimaries Come Early.\nIf Musgrove consents to run, he\nwill probably announce that he is\nnot anxious to obtain delegates for\nhimself; that he is a symbol of pro\ntest again the high-handedness of\nthe Underwood forces and that, if\nhe wins, he will appoint delegates\nfrom among the nominees in the\norder of their strength.\nThe Alabama primaries will be\nheld in March. If Underwood\nshould be defeated thus early his\nenemies anticipate it would crush\nhim nationally. The man who de\nfeats him would become overnight a\ncelebrity.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES The National Daily FRIDAY, DECEMBER 21, 1923.\nMAJ. HOUTSONG\nHURT IN AUTO\nPLUNGE\nVeterans\u2019 Bureau Official Is in\nCritical Condition, Hos\npital Reports.\nMaj. Ralph C. Routsong, chief of\nthe plan and statistics division of\nthe Veterans\u2019 Bureau, is in a semi\nconscious condition at Walter Reed\nHospital today with only a slight\nchance for recovery, following an au\ntomobile accident near Burnt Mills,\nMd., last night- Doctors declare he\nhas a double fracture of the skull.\nHarold C. Breining, assistant di\nrector of the financial division of\nthe Veterans\u2019 Bureau, Is confined at\nhis home, 1434 Harvard street north\nwest, 'where he was taken shortly\nafter the accident, with slight\nbruises.\nCar Turns Over.\nBreining and Major Routsong\nwere driving on the Brookville road,\nwhen their machine took a head\nlong dive over the embankment, and\nturned over. A passing autoist took\nthem to the hospital.\nEight others were injured in traf\nfic accidents in Washington yester\nday.\nContusions of the head were suf\nfered by William Miller, seven, 1227\nTwelfth street southeast, when he\nwas hit by an automobile in front of\nhis home.\nPhillip Nethalia, twenty-five, 1414\nTwenty-fourth street northwest, re\nceived bruises on the head and arms.\nAfter treatment at Garfield hospital\nhe went home.\nOthers Slightly Injured.\nSlight injuries were sustained by\nthe following: Joseph Guardina, of\nThird and K streets northeast; Nelson\nBrooks, colored, 95 N street south\neast; James Corev, colored, 18 Purdy\nplace ndrthwest; Elizabeth Johnson,\n1243 Slx-and-a-half street northwest,\nand Dix Washington, colored, 1261\nNew Jersey avenue southeast.\nN. J. to Attack Fake Doctors.\nTRENTON, N. J., Dec. 21.\u2014The\nState board of medical examiners an\nnounced that it would ask the legis\nlature to compel physicians to ob\ntain certificates of registration an\nnually.\nOur 9th St. and Pa. Ave. Stores Open Till 9\n\nMen\u2019s Dress Shoes\nfor Christmas and New Year\u2019s\nPatent Leather Dancing Oxfords\n$5 $7.50 $lO\n\u201cFlorsheim\u201d Full Dress Shoes, d* 1 n\nwith cloth tops, as pictured\"\nWinding Up These Big\nMEN\u2019S SLIPPER SALES\ncy.\nWhat a sale this has Good-looking tan leather\nOpera, Everett and Elastic-\nbeen! Warm, cheery felts si< i e Romeo House Slip\nwit h padded moccasin pera Such values that\nsoles\u2014regularly $1.25 and we\u2019ve been sold out on\nthem once already\u2014and\n$1.50 \u2014but no time to wj]l again, very soon!\nlose! Hurry!\nGive Him if\nSocks\nSilk or wool\u2014*or dress\nor sports\u2014such nifty se- v c\nlections- Cor. 7th Sts.\n414 9th St\n65c tO $2.50 \u2018'City Club Shafi\u201d 1914-16 Pa. Ave.\n1318 G St. 233 Pa. Ave. S.E.\nWHAT\u2019S DOING,\nI Today and Tomorrow\nToday.\nMeeting\u2014Business\u2019 Women\u2019s Council,\nlecture room of the Church of the Cov\nenant, 8 p. m.\nMeeting\u2014William McKinley Post. No.\n2. Ladies of the G. A. R., Grand Army\nHall, 8 p. m.\nChristmas celebration\u2014Sunday School,\nChurch of the Advent, 8 p. m.\nMeeting\u2014lnterdenominational com mi t-\nItee on prayer groups under the World\nConference on Faith and Order, Y. W.\nC. A., 1311 G street northwest, 2 p. m.\nChristmas assembly Central High\nSchool, auditorium. 9:15 p. m.\nMeeting\u2014Natives of the District of\nColumbia. Washington Club, 8 p. m.\nChristmas Oratorio\u2014\" Dawn In the\nDesert,\u2019\u2019 benefit Florence Crittenton\nHome, Keith\u2019s Theater, 12:30 p. m.\nReunion \u2014Alumni Association of East\nern High School, afternoon and eve\nning.\nAddress\u2014\u201clmmigration,\u201d Secretary of\nLabor Davis,' American Association of\nUniversity Women.\nChristmas Play\u2014Johnson-PowelJ Com\nmunity Center, evening.\nDeanwood Community Center\u2014Sewing\ncircle, dramatic club, music club, ath\nletic club, evening.\nPetworth\u2014Christmas entertainment by\nGirl Scouts and dramatic class.\nWilson Normal\u2014School girls play, 8;\nGirl Scouts, 7:30; Columbia Midgets,\n7:3O;>Junior Social Dancing Club. 8 p.m.\nBirney\u2014Junior dramatic club and\nrhythmic dancing class, 3; Criterion\nAthletic Club. Rialto -Athletic Club.\nGirls Athletic Club and Whittling Club,\n7:30\u2019t0 10:30 p. m.\nSoutheast\u2014Rythmic dancing class, 7;\nJunior dramatic class, 8 p. m.\nCleveland Phelps Americanization\nbasketball, 6; Girls Recreational Club, 4;\nNorth Carolina Club, sewing class, beauty\nculture, and millinery class, General\nCivic Association, Navy Department\nEmployes' Union, Amphlon Glee Club,\nnational educational board, 7:30 p. m.\nE. V. Ifrown \u2014Rhythm class, 3:15 p. m.\nMiner Normal Girls\u2019 needlework,\nboys\u2019 athletic, boys\u2019 basketball, girls\u2019\nathletic, girls\u2019 choral, young people's\ndramatic clubs, 7; women's needlework..\nmen's current events, Red Cross class\nIn home hygiene and care of the sick.\nRed Cross class In first aid. Adult Choral\nClub. 7:30 p. m.\nSocial Hour\u2014Beta Theta Pi Club,\nCosmos Club, 8:15 p. m.\nTomorrow.\nChristmas Bible Drama \u2014\u201cThe Word\nand the Way,\" Central High School, eve\nning.\nLovejoy Community Center Girls\u2019\nDressmaking Club, 11 a. m. Slides on\nOld Testament, 7:30; Boy Scouts, 7:30;\nRadio Club, Buffalo Athletic Club, Girls'\nAthletic Club, Bestyette Club, Once A\nWeek Club, 8:30,p. m.\nCleveland Phelps Class In rhythmic\ndancing, 10 a. m.\nCentral High School \u2014Pageant, \u201cThe\nWord and the Way.\u201d\nSoutheast\u2014Adult Dramatic Club, 8:30;\ndramatics for children, 7:30; girl athletes,\n7; E. M. S. athletic group, 9 p. m.\nJohnson-Powell\u2014Perry Athletic Club,\nArgyle Athletic Club, Johnson-Powell\nalumni dance.\nS7OO Burned in Stove.\nSeven hundred dollars In cash was\nburned in a fire resulting from an\nexplosion of an oil stove in the home\nof Phillip W. Boone, 4408 Lane place\nnortheast, last night. The money\nwas hidden in a closet that caught\nfire. The fire did SSO damage besides\nthis.\nVI. SOCIETY TO\nHOLD BALL\nJ1N.24\nFinal Arrangements for Recep\ntion to Cpngress Delegation\nCompleted.\nFinal arrangements were made\nlast night at a meeting of the State\nof Virginia Society in the Raleigh\nHotel for the reception and ball\nthat will be tendered the Virginia\nCongressional delegation January 24.\nGen. H. Oden Lake, president of\nthe society, was appointed general\nchairman of the committees. Other\ncommittees appointed Were:\nFloor Committee, E. Lodge Hill,\nchairman; Fenton Leith, A. C.\nSmith, Jesse Anthony, Col. C. N.\nJoyce, Rodney L. Lynn, Lieut. R.\nH. Lake, C. O. Whaley, Charles M.\nOsborne.\nReception committee, Maj. E. W.\nR. Ewing, chairman; Mrs. R. H.\nBagby, John W. Daniels, 111, Mes\ndames Enid K. Anthony, Winifred\nFoerster, Nellie V. Suess, E. C. R.\nHumphries, Jessie Edes, John H.\nNelsoii.\nEntertainment committee, Mrs.\nMargaret deClare M. Berry, chair\nman; Mesdames Sadie Ford Hutton,\nEdna Bishop Daniels, Annie G. Or\nrison, Miss Mary Louise Melvin.\nMesdames Lillian A. Lak, C. O.\nWhaley, C. W. Coughlin, Sue E.\nRamey.\nCongressional committee, F. C.\nBaggarly, chairman; Hon. George C.\nPeery, William H. Saunders, Hon.\nJ. C. Byars, G. E. Dunkum.\nInvitation and printing commit\ntee, Mrs. Enid K. Anthony, chair\nman; Mrs. Edna F. Long, Miss Alice\nRogers, Miss Sallie McVeigh, Mrs.\nMay L. Isbell.\nPress committee, Col. E. C. R.\nHumphries, chairman.\nHall and music committee, Her\nbert H. Davis, chairman; George\nGibson, Fred O. Lake, D. D. Isbell.\nYOUTH PICKETS HOME\nTO GET CHORE WAGES\nST. PAUL, Minn., Dec. 21.\u2014Be\ncause his father, an attorney, had\npostponed payment for chores done,\nfourteen-year-old J. C. Otis, jr., of\nthis city, picketed his home wearing\na sign, \u201cThis house is unfair to la\nbor.\u201d\nOtis paid up and the sign went in\ndoors.\n0.0. RAILWAYS\nHEARING NEXT\nMONTH\nSenator Ball Announces Main\nPoints Committee Will\nConsider.\nSpurred by the Insistence of Sen\nator McKellar upon his 5-cent fare\nresolution, the Senate District Com\nmittee will begin hearings upon the\nlocal street railway situation next\nmonth, Senator L. Heisler Ball an\nnounced today. The specific points\nto which the inquiry will be ad\ndressed are:\nThe consolidation of the bus lines\nwith the traction companies under\none directing\u2019 head, with revised\nroutes for the busses, which will\nmake them feeders of the suburban\ntraction lines rather thgn direct com\npetitors in the city.\nThe substitution of a per centum\ntax on the net income of the street\nrailway companies in place of the\nexisting 4 per cent tax on gross in\ncome.\nBail\u2019s Tax Views.\nSenator Ball declares that the\npresent tax forces the Washington\nRailway and Electric Company with\nsmaller net earnings than thR Capi\ntal Traction Company to pay as\nmuch money into the District cof\nfers as does the latter, because its\ngross earnings are about as large.\nPracticability of a 5-cent fare for\nthe Capital Traction Company, it be\ning admitted that the Washington\nRailway and 'Electric Company would\noperate at a loss under such a fare\non the basis of its present valuation.\nA tax on the net earnings of the\nbuslines identical with that proposed\nIS AV IT WITH~\n\u201cCity Club Shop\u201d St.\nI C \u00b0L R J\u2014 wfa\nThe Young People Will Thank\n\u201cOld Nick\u201d for Gifts of\n\u201cGro-nups\u201d Shoes!\nq TXT S /Ml IWa i\nBoy\u2019s Brown \u2019LI Girls\u2019 Play Hjt SWfjEl\nElk Blucher W Shoes RSh Black Shoes\n$3.45 to Lgfl !\u2018K\nITMMggr/wffi?\nvj Pv\nfM Children\u2019s 2T lagk,' \u201ejp\nJl/jivjW Fancy-top i\u00df \u2122HfiSl Small Boy\u2019s\nWW\u00ae[ Novelties Boy s Tan Eric BK Dress Shoe\n$4.50 to $5 Calf Blucher $4.50 to $5.50\nmi I MU-A /1 II\n\u00aei '\u00aeE&- Ms\nY|l 'J .jg \u201cStorm. jMfJn j\nI 0 King\" SM I Rea-t \u00b0I il J\nI lll* Rubber RQa| S lia WSS M W Boots AII 1\nW -1 \u2018\u201c'\u2019\u201c\"\"ktf s'\u201d'\" O HH W w to\nWastes SB $3-5# to ml Children\u2019s Ng f J' $3.45 |Mg\u00a37\nI MF $4.50 KW Bootees KM iu|\nv wtm A (ISr AU colors u|H WJL H& Jy\n4\nOTFfTI/VP\nInfants\u2019 Lace BBC Boy 9 L J\nSh e Noveltlcs I\u00a7| $4.50 to $5 MRo\nfi |Sm $4.50 to $5 KM $2.75 to $4.50 |gg MU< ft\ni IB l -jp\n1 fl Popular Sports Hose 1\nFor Girls and Boys g\nAn immense variety of the popular Roll-lop\nJI Sports Stockings and Socks. All wanted colors\njls i'\u25a0<\u2022'\u2022 at the price you want to pay.\n1-10:11 55c 75c SI.OO $1.19 $1.69 WoiM\nU *IM X-liual\nU. S. Is Far Largest\nBuyer Os Cut\nFlowers\nAmerica spends more money\nfor cut flowers annually than\nany nation in the world, Govern-\nment officials said today. No\nofficial estimate of the figure\nis yet available.\nMillions are expended during\nevery Christmas season. The\nnext best flower market comes\naround Easter and the third in\nthe June bride period.\nTne flower export, how\u2019ever,\nis small, having amounted in the\nfirst ten months of this year to\nbut $85,000. Most of the export\nwent to Canada. Twenty dol\nlars worth of cut flowers were\nsent to England and $8 vrorth to\nJapan, the Flower Kingdom.\nfor the two street railway corpora\ntions and an extra paving tax for\nthem because of Jhe wear and tear\nthey put upon the city streets.\nElimination of the present system\nof compelling the traction companies\nto pay the salaries of crossing po\nlicemen and of paving between their\ntracks.\nMcKellar Bars Compromise.\nBall is inclined to believe that some\nreduction in fares would be possible\nif the companies were given exemp\ntion from these charges.\nRenewed consideration of the Pub\nlic Utilities Commission bill which\nimposes an excess profits tax on the\ntraction companies with the idea of\nremoving their present objections to\na merger.\nIn the meantime, McKellar has\nspurned all proposals of compromise\nand delay for his 5-cent fare bill, be\nlieving that the \u201ccards are stacked\nagainst him\u201d in the District Com\nmittee. He will proceed with his\npolicy of making the road for all\nDistrict legislation as rough and\ndangerous as possible.\nSOLDIER BONUS\nTO COME IIP\nEARLY\nAdvocates Plan to Compel Con**\nsideration When House\nMeets in January.\nThe soldier bonus bill will be\nthrust before the House immedi\nately after Congress reconvenes\nJanuary 3, according to plans ma\ntured today by bonus advocates.\nUnless the Ways and Means Com\nmittee is ready then to begin con\nsideration of the McKenzie bill,\nwhich is backed by the American\nLegionT, a Republican conference\nwill be forced and this c6nference\nwill instruct the committee to bring\nout the bill, bonus advocates said\ntod&y\nRepublican Leader Longworth ex- 4\npects the Ways and Means Com\nmittee to finish its study of the\nadministrative and simplification\nfeatures of the existing tax laws\nearly in January- Committee mem\nbers said today they had made good\nprogress with consideration of this\nlegislation and had found little in\nthe recommendations of Secretary\nMellon of such a controversial char\nacter as to necessitate lengthy con\nsideration.\nCompromises in the bonus legis\nlation ire being sought. A new\nplan suggested is that the former\nservice men entitled to it shall\nhave refunded to them in lieu of the\nbonus, money they paid for in\nsurance and their contributions to\nthe support of dependents while\nthey were in the service.","height":"26820","width":"22416"}}
